# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: kedro-pipelines
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] Data science plays a critical role in modern decision-making by enabling organizations to extract actionable insights from large and complex datasets.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] Data science also integrates domain knowledge from the underlying application domain (e.g., natural sciences, information technology, and medicine).
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] Data science is multifaceted and can be described as a science, a research paradigm, a research method, a discipline, a workflow, and a profession.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] Data science is "a concept to unify statistics, data analysis, informatics, and their related methods" to "understand and analyze actual phenomena" with data.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] It uses techniques and theories drawn from many fields within the context of mathematics, statistics, computer science, information science, and domain knowledge.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] However, data science is distinct from computer science and information science.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] Turing Award winner Jim Gray imagined data science as a "fourth paradigm" of science (empirical, theoretical, computational, and now data-driven) and asserted that "everything about science is changing because of the impact of information technology" and the data deluge.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] Data science is often described as a multidisciplinary and rapidly evolving field because it draws on techniques from diverse areas, such as computer science, statistics, information science, and other subject-specific disciplines.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] Some researchers argue that the combination of the different fields resembles how information science was decades ago.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] These similarities help clarify how data science gradually became its own field of study.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] Data science is an interdisciplinary field focused on extracting knowledge from typically large data sets and applying the knowledge from that data to solve problems in other application domains.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] The field encompasses preparing data for analysis, formulating data science problems, analyzing data, and summarizing these findings.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] As such, it incorporates skills from computer science, mathematics, data visualization, graphic design, communication, and business.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] Vasant Dhar writes that statistics emphasizes quantitative data and description.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] In contrast, data science deals with quantitative and qualitative data (e.g., from images, text, sensors, transactions, customer information, etc.) and emphasizes prediction and action.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] Andrew Gelman of Columbia University has described statistics as a non-essential part of data science.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] Stanford professor David Donoho writes that data science is not distinguished from statistics by the size of datasets or use of computing and that many graduate programs misleadingly advertise their analytics and statistics training as the essence of a data-science program.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] He describes data science as an applied field growing out of traditional statistics.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] In 1962, John Tukey described a field he called "data analysis", which resembles modern data science.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] In 1985, in a lecture given to the Chinese Academy of Sciences in Beijing, C.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] Jeff Wu used the term "data science" for the first time as an alternative name for statistics.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] Later, attendees at a 1992 statistics symposium at the University of Montpellier II acknowledged the emergence of a new discipline focused on data of various origins and forms, combining established concepts and principles of statistics and data analysis with computing.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] The term "data science" has been traced back to 1974, when Peter Naur proposed it as an alternative name to computer science.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] However, the definition was still in flux.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] After the 1985 lecture at the Chinese Academy of Sciences in Beijing, in 1997 C.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] Jeff Wu again suggested that statistics should be renamed data science.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] He reasoned that a new name would help statistics shed inaccurate stereotypes, such as being synonymous with accounting or limited to describing data.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] In 1998, Hayashi Chikio argued for data science as a new, interdisciplinary concept, with three aspects: data design, collection, and analysis.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] Davenport and DJ Patil declared "Data Scientist: The Sexiest Job of the 21st Century", a catchphrase that was picked up even by major-city newspapers like the *New York Times* and the *Boston Globe*.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] A decade later, they reaffirmed it, stating that "the job is more in demand than ever with employers".
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] The modern conception of data science as an independent discipline is sometimes attributed to William S.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] In 2014, the American Statistical Association's Section on Statistical Learning and Data Mining changed its name to the Section on Statistical Learning and Data Science, reflecting the ascendant popularity of data science.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] The professional title of "data scientist" has been attributed to DJ Patil and Jeff Hammerbacher in 2008.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] Though it was used by the National Science Board in their 2005 report "Long-Lived Digital Data Collections: Enabling Research and Education in the 21st Century", it referred broadly to any key role in managing a digital data collection.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] Data analysis typically involves working with structured datasets to answer specific questions or solve specific problems.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] This can involve tasks such as data cleaning and data visualization to summarize data and develop hypotheses about relationships between variables.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] Data analysts typically use statistical methods to test these hypotheses and draw conclusions from the data.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] Data science involves working with larger datasets that often require advanced computational and statistical methods to analyze.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] Data scientists often work with unstructured data such as text or images and use machine learning algorithms to build predictive models.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] Data science often uses statistical analysis, data preprocessing, and supervised learning.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] Cloud computing can offer access to large amounts of computational power and storage.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] In big data, where volumes of information are continually generated and processed, these platforms can be used to handle complex and resource-intensive analytical tasks.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] Some distributed computing frameworks are designed to handle big data workloads.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] These frameworks can enable data scientists to process and analyze large datasets in parallel, which can reduce processing times.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] Data science involves collecting, processing, and analyzing data which often includes personal and sensitive information.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] Ethical concerns include potential privacy violations, bias perpetuation, and negative societal impacts.
[src:kedro-pipelines/data-science] Machine learning models can amplify existing biases present in training data, leading to discriminatory or unfair outcomes.
[src:kedro-pipelines/kedro-concepts] This page introduces the most basic elements of Kedro.
[src:kedro-pipelines/kedro-concepts] You can find further information about these and more advanced Kedro concepts in the Kedro glossary.
[src:kedro-pipelines/kedro-concepts] You may prefer to skip to the next section to create a Kedro project for hands-on Kedro experience.
[src:kedro-pipelines/kedro-concepts] In Kedro, a node is a wrapper for a pure Python function that names the inputs and outputs of that function.
[src:kedro-pipelines/kedro-concepts] Nodes are the building block of a pipeline, and the output of one node can be the input of another.
[src:kedro-pipelines/kedro-concepts] A pipeline organises the dependencies and execution order of a collection of nodes and connects inputs and outputs while keeping your code modular.
[src:kedro-pipelines/kedro-concepts] The pipeline determines the **node execution order** by resolving dependencies and does *not* necessarily run the nodes in the order in which they are passed in.
[src:kedro-pipelines/kedro-concepts] The Kedro Data Catalog is the registry of all data sources that the project can use to manage loading and saving data.
[src:kedro-pipelines/kedro-concepts] It maps the names of node inputs and outputs as keys in a `DataCatalog`, a Kedro class that can be specialised for different types of data storage.
[src:kedro-pipelines/kedro-concepts] Kedro provides different built-in datasets for several file types and file systems, so you don’t have to write the logic for reading/writing data.
[src:kedro-pipelines/kedro-concepts] One of the main advantages of working with Kedro projects is that they follow a default template that makes collaboration straightforward.
[src:kedro-pipelines/kedro-concepts] Kedro uses semantic naming to set up a default project with specific folders to store datasets, notebooks, configuration, and source code.
[src:kedro-pipelines/kedro-concepts] We recommend keeping the default Kedro project structure because it makes sharing projects with other Kedro users straightforward, although you can adapt the folder structure if you need to.
[src:kedro-pipelines/kedro-concepts] Starting from Kedro 0.19, when you create a new project with `kedro new`, you can customise the structure by selecting which tools to include.
[src:kedro-pipelines/kedro-concepts] Depending on your choices, the resulting structure may vary.
[src:kedro-pipelines/kedro-concepts] Below, we outline the default project structure when all tools are selected and give an example with no tools selected.
[src:kedro-pipelines/kedro-concepts] During `kedro new`, you can select which tools to include in your project.
[src:kedro-pipelines/kedro-concepts] The `conf` folder contains two subfolders for storing configuration information: `base` and `local`.
[src:kedro-pipelines/kedro-concepts] Use the `base` subfolder for project-specific settings to share across different installations (for example, with other users).
[src:kedro-pipelines/kedro-concepts] The `local` subfolder is specific to each user and installation and its contents is ignored by `git` (through inclusion in `.gitignore`).
[src:kedro-pipelines/kedro-concepts] Use the `local` subfolder for **settings that should not be shared**, such as access credentials, custom editor configuration, personal IDE configuration and other sensitive or personal content.
[src:kedro-pipelines/kedro-concepts] By default, Kedro creates one file, `credentials.yml`, in `conf/local`.
[src:kedro-pipelines/kedro-concepts] This subfolder contains the project's source code.
[src:kedro-pipelines/kedro-concepts] While the default Kedro structure is recommended for collaboration and standardisation, it is possible to adapt the folder structure if necessary.
[src:kedro-pipelines/kedro-concepts] This flexibility allows you to tailor the project to your needs while maintaining a consistent and recognisable structure.
[src:kedro-pipelines/kedro-concepts] When you organise code, keep the `pipeline_registry.py` and `settings.py` files in the `<your_project>/src/<your_project>` directory, where they are created by default.
[src:kedro-pipelines/kedro-concepts] The `pipeline_registry.py` file must include a `register_pipelines()` function that returns a `dict[str, Pipeline]`, which maps pipeline names to their corresponding `Pipeline` objects.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Statistics and mathematical optimisation methods compose the foundations of machine learning.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Data mining is a related field of study, focusing on exploratory data analysis (EDA) through unsupervised learning.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] From a theoretical viewpoint, probably approximately correct learning provides a mathematical and statistical framework for describing machine learning.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Most traditional machine learning and deep learning algorithms can be described as empirical risk minimisation under this framework.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] The term *machine learning* was coined in 1959 by Arthur Samuel, an IBM employee and pioneer in the field of computer gaming and artificial intelligence.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] The synonym *self-teaching computers* was also used during this time period.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] The earliest machine learning program was introduced in the 1950s, when Samuel invented a computer program that calculated the chance of winning in checkers for each side, but the history of machine learning is rooted in decades of efforts to study human cognitive processes.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] In 1949, Canadian psychologist Donald Hebb published the book *The Organization of Behavior*, in which he introduced a theoretical neural structure formed by certain interactions among nerve cells.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] The Hebbian theory of neuron interaction set the groundwork for how many machine learning algorithms work, with connected artificial neurons changing the strength of their connections based on data.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Other researchers who have studied human cognitive systems contributed to the modern machine learning technologies as well, including Walter Pitts and Warren McCulloch, who proposed the first mathematical model of neural networks including algorithms that mirror human thought processes.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] By the early 1960s, an experimental "learning machine" with punched tape memory, called Cybertron, had been developed by Raytheon Company to analyse sonar signals, electrocardiograms, and speech patterns using rudimentary reinforcement learning.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] It was repetitively "trained" by a human operator/teacher to recognise patterns and equipped with a "goof" button to cause it to reevaluate incorrect decisions.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] A representative book on research into machine learning during the 1960s was Nils Nilsson's book "Learning Machines", dealing mostly with machine learning for pattern classification.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Interest related to pattern recognition continued into the 1970s, as described by Duda and Hart in 1973.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] In 1981, a report was given on using teaching strategies so that an artificial neural network learns to recognise 40 characters (26 letters, 10 digits, and 4 special symbols) from a computer terminal.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] This follows Alan Turing's proposal in his paper "Computing Machinery and Intelligence", in which the question, "Can machines think?", is replaced by asking whether machines can convincingly imitate a human in its responses to human-posed questions.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] In 2014 Ian Goodfellow and others introduced generative adversarial networks (GANs) which could produce realistic synthetic data.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] By 2016 AlphaGo had won against top human players in Go using reinforcement learning techniques.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] As a scientific endeavour, machine learning grew out of the quest for artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] In the early days of AI as an academic discipline, some researchers were interested in having machines learn from data.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] They attempted to approach the problem with various symbolic methods, as well as what were then termed "neural networks"; these were mostly perceptrons and other models that were later found to be reinventions of the generalised linear models of statistics.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Probabilistic reasoning was also employed, especially in automated medical diagnosis.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] However, an increasing emphasis on the logical, knowledge-based approach caused a rift between AI and machine learning.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Probabilistic systems were plagued by theoretical and practical problems of data acquisition and representation.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] By 1980, expert systems had come to dominate AI, and statistics was out of favour.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Work on symbolic/knowledge-based learning continued within AI, leading to inductive logic programming (ILP), but the more statistical line of research was now outside the field of AI proper, in pattern recognition and information retrieval.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Neural network research was abandoned by AI and computer science around the same time.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] This subfield, termed "connectionism", was continued by researchers from other disciplines, including John Hopfield, David Rumelhart, and Geoffrey Hinton.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Their main success came in the mid-1980s with the reinvention of backpropagation.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning (ML), reorganised and recognised as its own field, started to flourish in the 1990s.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] The field changed its goal from achieving artificial intelligence to tackling solvable problems of a practical nature.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] It shifted focus away from the symbolic approaches it had inherited from AI, and toward methods and models borrowed from statistics, fuzzy logic, and probability theory.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] There is a close connection between machine learning and compression.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] A system that predicts the posterior probabilities of a sequence given its entire history can be used for optimal data compression (by using arithmetic coding on the output distribution).
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Conversely, an optimal compressor can be used for prediction (by finding the symbol that compresses best, given the previous history).
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] This equivalence has been used as a justification for using data compression as a benchmark for "general intelligence".
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] An alternative view can show compression algorithms implicitly map strings into implicit feature space vectors, and compression-based similarity measures compute similarity within these feature spaces.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] For each compressor C(.) we define an associated vector space ℵ, such that C(.) maps an input string x, corresponding to the vector norm ||~x||.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] An exhaustive examination of the feature spaces underlying all compression algorithms is precluded by space; instead, feature vectors chooses to examine three representative lossless compression methods, LZW, LZ77, and PPM.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] According to AIXI theory, a connection more directly explained in Hutter Prize, the best possible compression of x is the smallest possible software that generates x.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] For example, in that model, a zip file's compressed size includes both the zip file and the unzipping software, since you can not unzip it without both, but there may be an even smaller combined form.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Examples of AI-powered audio/video compression software include NVIDIA Maxine, AIVC.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Examples of software that can perform AI-powered image compression include OpenCV, TensorFlow, MATLAB's Image Processing Toolbox (IPT) and High-Fidelity Generative Image Compression.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] In unsupervised machine learning, k-means clustering can be utilized to compress data by grouping similar data points into clusters.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] This technique simplifies handling extensive datasets that lack predefined labels and finds widespread use in fields such as image compression.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Data compression aims to reduce the size of data files, enhancing storage efficiency and speeding up data transmission.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] K-means clustering, an unsupervised machine learning algorithm, is employed to partition a dataset into a specified number of clusters, k, each represented by the centroid of its points.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] This process condenses extensive datasets into a more compact set of representative points.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Particularly beneficial in image and signal processing, k-means clustering aids in data reduction by replacing groups of data points with their centroids, thereby preserving the core information of the original data while significantly decreasing the required storage space.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Large language models (LLMs) are also efficient lossless data compressors on some data sets, as demonstrated by DeepMind's research with the Chinchilla 70B model.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Developed by DeepMind, Chinchilla 70B effectively compressed data, outperforming conventional methods such as Portable Network Graphics (PNG) for images and Free Lossless Audio Codec (FLAC) for audio.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] It achieved compression of image and audio data to 43.4% and 16.4% of their original sizes, respectively.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] There is, however, some reason to be concerned that the data set used for testing overlaps the LLM training data set, making it possible that the Chinchilla 70B model is only an efficient compression tool on data it has already been trained on.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Data mining uses many machine learning methods, but with different goals; on the other hand, machine learning also employs data mining methods as "unsupervised learning" or as a preprocessing step to improve learner accuracy.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Evaluated with respect to known knowledge, an uninformed (unsupervised) method will easily be outperformed by other supervised methods, while in a typical KDD task, supervised methods cannot be used due to the unavailability of training data.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning also has intimate ties to optimization: Many learning problems are formulated as minimisation of some loss function on a training set of examples.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Loss functions express the discrepancy between the predictions of the model being trained and the actual problem instances (for example, in classification, one wants to assign a label to instances, and models are trained to correctly predict the preassigned labels of a set of examples).
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Characterizing the generalisation of various learning algorithms is an active topic of current research, especially for deep learning algorithms.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning and statistics are closely related fields in terms of methods, but distinct in their principal goal: statistics draws population inferences from a sample, while machine learning finds generalisable predictive patterns.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Conventional statistical analyses require the a priori selection of a model most suitable for the study data set.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] In addition, only significant or theoretically relevant variables based on previous experience are included for analysis.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] In contrast, machine learning is not built on a pre-structured model; rather, the data shape the model by detecting underlying patterns.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] The more variables (input) used to train the model, the more accurate the ultimate model will be.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Leo Breiman distinguished two statistical modelling paradigms: the data model and the algorithmic model, wherein "algorithmic model" means more or less the machine learning algorithms like Random forest.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Some statisticians have adopted methods from machine learning, producing the field of *statistical learning*.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Analytical and computational techniques derived from deep-rooted physics of disordered systems can be extended to large-scale problems, including machine learning, e.g., to analyse the weight space of deep neural networks.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Statistical physics is thus finding applications in the area of medical diagnostics.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] A core objective of a learner is to generalise from its experience.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Generalisation in this context is the ability of a learning machine to perform accurately on new, unseen examples/tasks after having experienced a learning data set.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] The training examples come from some generally unknown probability distribution (considered representative of the space of occurrences) and the learner has to build a general model about this space that enables it to produce sufficiently accurate predictions in new cases.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] The computational analysis of machine learning algorithms and their performance is a branch of theoretical computer science known as computational learning theory.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] One major framework is the probably approximately correct learning model.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Because training sets are finite and the future is uncertain, learning theory usually does not yield guarantees of the performance of algorithms.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Instead, probabilistic bounds on the performance are quite common.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] The bias–variance decomposition is one way to quantify generalisation error.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] For the best performance in the context of generalisation, the complexity of the hypothesis should match the complexity of the function underlying the data.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] If the hypothesis is less complex than the function, then the model has underfitted the data.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] If the complexity of the model is increased in response, then the training error decreases.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] But if the hypothesis is too complex, then the model is subject to overfitting and generalisation will be poorer.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] In addition to performance bounds, learning theorists study the time complexity and feasibility of learning.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] In computational learning theory, a computation is considered feasible if it can be done in polynomial time.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] There are two kinds of time complexity results: Positive results show that a certain class of functions can be learned in polynomial time.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Negative results show that certain classes cannot be learned in polynomial time.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Although each algorithm has advantages and limitations, no single algorithm works for all problems.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Supervised learning algorithms build a mathematical model of a set of data that contains both the inputs and the desired outputs.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] The data, known as training data, consists of a set of training examples.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Each training example has one or more inputs and the desired output, also known as a supervisory signal.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] In the mathematical model, each training example is represented by an array or vector, sometimes called a feature vector, and the training data is represented by a matrix.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Through iterative optimisation of an objective function, supervised learning algorithms learn a function that can be used to predict the output associated with new inputs.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] An optimal function allows the algorithm to correctly determine the output for inputs that were not a part of the training data.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] An algorithm that improves the accuracy of its outputs or predictions over time is said to have learned to perform that task.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Types of supervised-learning algorithms include active learning, classification and regression.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Classification algorithms are used when the outputs are restricted to a limited set of values, while regression algorithms are used when the outputs can take any numerical value within a range.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] For example, in a classification algorithm that filters emails, the input is an incoming email, and the output is the folder in which to file the email.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] In contrast, regression is used for tasks such as predicting a person's height based on factors like age and genetics or forecasting future temperatures based on historical data.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Similarity learning is an area of supervised machine learning closely related to regression and classification, but the goal is to learn from examples using a similarity function that measures how similar or related two objects are.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] It has applications in ranking, recommendation systems, visual identity tracking, face verification, and speaker verification.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Unsupervised learning algorithms find structures in data that has not been labelled, classified or categorised.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Instead of responding to feedback, unsupervised learning algorithms identify commonalities in the data and react based on the presence or absence of such commonalities in each new piece of data.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Central applications of unsupervised machine learning include clustering, dimensionality reduction, and density estimation.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Cluster analysis is the assignment of a set of observations into subsets (called *clusters*) so that observations within the same cluster are similar according to one or more predesignated criteria, while observations drawn from different clusters are dissimilar.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Different clustering techniques make different assumptions on the structure of the data, often defined by some *similarity metric* and evaluated, for example, by *internal compactness*, or the similarity between members of the same cluster, and *separation*, the difference between clusters.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Other methods are based on *estimated density* and *graph connectivity*.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] A special type of unsupervised learning called self-supervised learning involves training a model by generating the supervisory signal from the data itself.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Dimensionality reduction is a process of reducing the number of random variables under consideration by obtaining a set of principal variables.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] In other words, it is a process of reducing the dimension of the feature set, also called the "number of features".
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Most of the dimensionality reduction techniques can be considered as either feature elimination or extraction.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] One of the popular methods of dimensionality reduction is principal component analysis (PCA).
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] PCA involves changing higher-dimensional data (e.g., 3D) to a smaller space (e.g., 2D).
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] The manifold hypothesis proposes that high-dimensional data sets lie along low-dimensional manifolds, and many dimensionality reduction techniques make this assumption, leading to the areas of manifold learning and manifold regularisation.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Semi-supervised learning falls between unsupervised learning (without any labelled training data) and supervised learning (with completely labelled training data).
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Some of the training examples are missing training labels, yet many machine-learning researchers have found that unlabelled data, when used in conjunction with a small amount of labelled data, can produce a considerable improvement in learning accuracy.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] In weakly supervised learning, the training labels are noisy, limited, or imprecise; however, these labels are often cheaper to obtain, resulting in larger effective training sets.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Reinforcement learning is an area of machine learning concerned with how software agents ought to take actions in an environment to maximise some notion of cumulative reward.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Due to its generality, the field is studied in many other disciplines, such as game theory, control theory, operations research, information theory, simulation-based optimisation, multi-agent systems, swarm intelligence, statistics and genetic algorithms.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] In reinforcement learning, the environment is typically represented as a Markov decision process (MDP).
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Many reinforcement learning algorithms use dynamic programming techniques.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Reinforcement learning algorithms do not assume knowledge of an exact mathematical model of the MDP and are used when exact models are infeasible.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Reinforcement learning algorithms are used in autonomous vehicles or in learning to play a game against a human opponent.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Other approaches have been developed which do not fit neatly into this three-fold categorisation, and sometimes more than one is used by the same machine learning system.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] For example, topic modelling, meta-learning.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Self-learning, as a machine learning paradigm, was introduced in 1982 along with a neural network capable of self-learning, named *crossbar adaptive array* (CAA).
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] It gives a solution to the problem learning without any external reward, by introducing emotion as an internal reward.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Emotion is used as a state evaluation of a self-learning agent.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] The CAA self-learning algorithm computes, in a crossbar fashion, both decisions about actions and emotions (feelings) about consequence situations.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] The system is driven by the interaction between cognition and emotion.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] It is a system with only one input, situation, and only one output, action (or behaviour) a.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] There is neither a separate reinforcement input nor an advice input from the environment.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] The backpropagated value (secondary reinforcement) is the emotion toward the consequence situation.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] The CAA exists in two environments, one is the behavioural environment where it behaves, and the other is the genetic environment, wherefrom it initially and only once receives initial emotions about situations to be encountered in the behavioural environment.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] After receiving the genome (species) vector from the genetic environment, the CAA learns a goal-seeking behaviour in an environment that contains both desirable and undesirable situations.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Several learning algorithms aim at discovering better representations of the inputs provided during training.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Classic examples include principal component analysis and cluster analysis.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Feature learning algorithms, also called representation learning algorithms, often attempt to preserve the information in their input but also transform it in a way that makes it useful, often as a pre-processing step before performing classification or predictions.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] This technique allows reconstruction of the inputs coming from the unknown data-generating distribution, while not being necessarily faithful to configurations that are implausible under that distribution.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] This replaces manual feature engineering, and allows a machine to both learn the features and use them to perform a specific task.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Feature learning can be either supervised or unsupervised.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] In supervised feature learning, features are learned using labelled input data.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Examples include artificial neural networks, multilayer perceptrons, and supervised dictionary learning.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] In unsupervised feature learning, features are learned with unlabelled input data.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Examples include dictionary learning, independent component analysis, autoencoders, matrix factorisation and various forms of clustering.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Manifold learning algorithms attempt to do so under the constraint that the learned representation is low-dimensional.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Sparse coding algorithms attempt to do so under the constraint that the learned representation is sparse, meaning that the mathematical model has many zeros.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Multilinear subspace learning algorithms aim to learn low-dimensional representations directly from tensor representations for multidimensional data, without reshaping them into higher-dimensional vectors.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Deep learning algorithms discover multiple levels of representation, or a hierarchy of features, with higher-level, more abstract features defined in terms of (or generating) lower-level features.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] It has been argued that an intelligent machine learns a representation that disentangles the underlying factors of variation that explain the observed data.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Feature learning is motivated by the fact that machine learning tasks such as classification often require input that is mathematically and computationally convenient to process.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] However, real-world data such as images, video, and sensory data have not yielded attempts to algorithmically define specific features.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] An alternative is to discover such features or representations through examination, without relying on explicit algorithms.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Sparse dictionary learning is a feature learning method where a training example is represented as a linear combination of basis functions and assumed to be a sparse matrix.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] The method is strongly NP-hard and difficult to solve approximately.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] A popular heuristic method for sparse dictionary learning is the *k*-SVD algorithm.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Sparse dictionary learning has been applied in several contexts.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] In classification, the problem is to determine the class to which a previously unseen training example belongs.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] For a dictionary where each class has already been built, a new training example is associated with the class that is best sparsely represented by the corresponding dictionary.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Sparse dictionary learning has also been applied in image denoising.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] The key idea is that a clean image patch can be sparsely represented by an image dictionary, but the noise cannot.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] In data mining, anomaly detection, also known as outlier detection, is the identification of rare items, events or observations that raise suspicions by differing significantly from the majority of the data.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Typically, the anomalous items represent an issue such as bank fraud, a structural defect, medical problems or errors in a text.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Anomalies are referred to as outliers, novelties, noise, deviations and exceptions.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] In particular, in the context of abuse and network intrusion detection, the interesting objects are often not rare, but unexpected bursts of inactivity.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] This pattern does not adhere to the common statistical definition of an outlier as a rare object.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Many outlier detection methods (in particular, unsupervised algorithms) will fail on such data unless aggregated appropriately.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Instead, a cluster analysis algorithm may be able to detect the micro-clusters formed by these patterns.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Three broad categories of anomaly detection techniques exist.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Unsupervised anomaly detection techniques detect anomalies in an unlabelled test data set under the assumption that the majority of the instances in the data set are normal, by looking for instances that seem to fit the least to the remainder of the data set.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Supervised anomaly detection techniques require a data set that has been labelled as "normal" and "abnormal" and involves training a classifier (the key difference from many other statistical classification problems is the inherently unbalanced nature of outlier detection).
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Semi-supervised anomaly detection techniques construct a model representing normal behaviour from a given normal training data set and then test the likelihood of a test instance being generated by the model.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Robot learning is inspired by a multitude of machine learning methods, starting from supervised learning, reinforcement learning, and finally meta-learning (e.g.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Association rule learning is a rule-based machine learning method for discovering relationships between variables in large databases.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] It is intended to identify strong rules discovered in databases using some measure of "interestingness".
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Rule-based machine learning is a general term for any machine learning method that identifies, learns, or evolves "rules" to store, manipulate or apply knowledge.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] The defining characteristic of a rule-based machine learning algorithm is the identification and utilisation of a set of relational rules that collectively represent the knowledge captured by the system.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] This is in contrast to other machine learning algorithms that commonly identify a singular model that can be universally applied to any instance in order to make a prediction.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Rule-based machine learning approaches include learning classifier systems, association rule learning, and artificial immune systems.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Based on the concept of strong rules, Rakesh Agrawal, Tomasz Imieliński and Arun Swami introduced association rules for discovering regularities between products in large-scale transaction data recorded by point-of-sale (POS) systems in supermarkets.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] For example, the rule $\{\mathrm {onions,potatoes} \}\Rightarrow \{\mathrm {burger} \}$ found in the sales data of a supermarket would indicate that if a customer buys onions and potatoes together, they are likely to also buy hamburger meat.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Such information can be used as the basis for decisions about marketing activities such as promotional pricing or product placements.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] In addition to market basket analysis, association rules are employed today in application areas including Web usage mining, intrusion detection, continuous production, and bioinformatics.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] In contrast with sequence mining, association rule learning typically does not consider the order of items either within a transaction or across transactions.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Learning classifier systems (LCS) are a family of rule-based machine learning algorithms that combine a discovery component, typically a genetic algorithm, with a learning component, performing either supervised learning, reinforcement learning, or unsupervised learning.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] They seek to identify a set of context-dependent rules that collectively store and apply knowledge in a piecewise manner to make predictions.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Inductive logic programming (ILP) is an approach to rule learning using logic programming as a uniform representation for input examples, background knowledge, and hypotheses.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Given an encoding of the known background knowledge and a set of examples represented as a logical database of facts, an ILP system will derive a hypothesized logic program that entails all positive and no negative examples.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Inductive programming is a related field that considers any kind of programming language for representing hypotheses (and not only logic programming), such as functional programs.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Inductive logic programming is particularly useful in bioinformatics and natural language processing.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Gordon Plotkin and Ehud Shapiro laid the initial theoretical foundation for inductive machine learning in a logical setting.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Shapiro built their first implementation (Model Inference System) in 1981: a Prolog program that inductively inferred logic programs from positive and negative examples.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] The term *inductive* here refers to philosophical induction, suggesting a theory to explain observed facts, rather than mathematical induction, proving a property for all members of a well-ordered set.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] A **machine learning model** is a type of mathematical model that, once "trained" on a given dataset, can be used to make predictions or classifications on new data.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] During training, a learning algorithm iteratively adjusts the model's internal parameters to minimise errors in its predictions.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] By extension, the term "model" can refer to several levels of specificity, from a general class of models and their associated learning algorithms to a fully trained model with all its internal parameters tuned.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Various types of models have been used and researched for machine learning systems, picking the best model for a task is called model selection.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neural networks (ANNs), or connectionist systems, are computing systems vaguely inspired by the biological neural networks that constitute animal brains.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Such systems "learn" to perform tasks by considering examples, generally without being programmed with any task-specific rules.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] An ANN is a model based on a collection of connected units or nodes called "artificial neurons", which loosely model the neurons in a biological brain.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Each connection, like the synapses in a biological brain, can transmit information, a "signal", from one artificial neuron to another.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] An artificial neuron that receives a signal can process it and then signal additional artificial neurons connected to it.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] In common ANN implementations, the signal at a connection between artificial neurons is a real number, and the output of each artificial neuron is computed by some non-linear function of the sum of its inputs.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] The connections between artificial neurons are called "edges".
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neurons and edges typically have a weight that adjusts as learning proceeds.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] The weight increases or decreases the strength of the signal at a connection.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neurons may have a threshold such that the signal is only sent if the aggregate signal crosses that threshold.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Typically, artificial neurons are aggregated into layers.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Different layers may perform different kinds of transformations on their inputs.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Signals travel from the first layer (the input layer) to the last layer (the output layer), possibly after traversing the layers multiple times.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] The original goal of the ANN approach was to solve problems in the same way that a human brain would.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] However, over time, attention moved to performing specific tasks, leading to deviations from biology.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neural networks have been used on a variety of tasks, including computer vision, speech recognition, machine translation, social network filtering, playing board and video games and medical diagnosis.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Deep learning consists of multiple hidden layers in an artificial neural network.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] This approach tries to model the way the human brain processes light and sound into vision and hearing.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Some successful applications of deep learning are computer vision and speech recognition.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Decision tree learning uses a decision tree as a predictive model to go from observations about an item (represented in the branches) to conclusions about the item's target value (represented in the leaves).
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] It is one of the predictive modelling approaches used in statistics, data mining, and machine learning.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Tree models where the target variable can take a discrete set of values are called classification trees; in these tree structures, leaves represent class labels, and branches represent conjunctions of features that lead to those class labels.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Decision trees where the target variable can take continuous values (typically real numbers) are called regression trees.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] In decision analysis, a decision tree can be used to visually and explicitly represent decisions and decision making.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] In data mining, a decision tree describes data, but the resulting classification tree can be an input for decision-making.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Random forest regression (RFR) falls under the umbrella of decision tree-based models.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] RFR is an ensemble learning method that builds multiple decision trees and averages their predictions to improve accuracy and to avoid overfitting.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] To build decision trees, RFR uses bootstrapped sampling; for instance, each decision tree is trained on random data from the training set.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] This random selection of RFR for training enables the model to reduce biased predictions and achieve a higher degree of accuracy.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] RFR generates independent decision trees, and it can work on single-output data as well as multiple regressor tasks.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] This makes RFR compatible to be use in various applications.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Support-vector machines (SVMs), also known as support-vector networks, are a set of related supervised learning methods used for classification and regression.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Given a set of training examples, each marked as belonging to one of two categories, an SVM training algorithm builds a model that predicts whether a new example falls into one category.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] An SVM training algorithm is a non-probabilistic, binary, linear classifier, although methods such as Platt scaling exist to use SVM in a probabilistic classification setting.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] In addition to performing linear classification, SVMs can efficiently perform a non-linear classification using what is called the kernel trick, implicitly mapping their inputs into high-dimensional feature spaces.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Regression analysis encompasses a large variety of statistical methods to estimate the relationship between input variables and their associated features.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Its most common form is linear regression, where a single line is drawn to best fit the given data according to a mathematical criterion such as ordinary least squares.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] The latter is often extended by regularisation methods to mitigate overfitting and bias, as in ridge regression.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Multivariate linear regression extends the concept of linear regression to handle multiple dependent variables simultaneously.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] This approach estimates the relationships between a set of input variables and several output variables by fitting a multidimensional linear model.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] It is particularly useful in scenarios where outputs are interdependent or share underlying patterns, such as predicting multiple economic indicators or reconstructing images, which are inherently multi-dimensional.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] A Bayesian network, belief network, or directed acyclic graphical model is a probabilistic graphical model that represents a set of random variables and their conditional independence with a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] For example, a Bayesian network could represent the probabilistic relationships between diseases and symptoms.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Given symptoms, the network can be used to compute the probabilities of the presence of various diseases.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Efficient algorithms exist that perform inference and learning.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Bayesian networks that model sequences of variables, like speech signals or protein sequences, are called dynamic Bayesian networks.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Generalisations of Bayesian networks that can represent and solve decision problems under uncertainty are called influence diagrams.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] A Gaussian process is a stochastic process in which every finite collection of the random variables in the process has a multivariate normal distribution, and it relies on a pre-defined covariance function, or kernel, that models how pairs of points relate to each other depending on their locations.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Given a set of observed points, or input–output examples, the distribution of the (unobserved) output of a new point as a function of its input data can be directly computed by looking at the observed points and the covariances between those points and the new, unobserved point.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Gaussian processes are popular surrogate models in Bayesian optimisation used to do hyperparameter optimisation.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] A genetic algorithm (GA) is a search algorithm and heuristic technique that mimics the process of natural selection, using methods such as mutation and crossover to generate new genotypes in the hope of finding good solutions to a given problem.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] In machine learning, genetic algorithms were used in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Conversely, machine learning techniques have been used to improve the performance of genetic and evolutionary algorithms.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] The theory of belief functions, also referred to as evidence theory or Dempster–Shafer theory, is a general framework for reasoning with uncertainty, with understood connections to other frameworks such as probability, possibility and imprecise probability theories.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] These theoretical frameworks can be thought of as a kind of learner and have some analogous properties of how evidence is combined (e.g., Dempster's rule of combination), just like how in a pmf-based Bayesian approach would combine probabilities.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] However, there are many caveats to these beliefs functions when compared to Bayesian approaches to incorporate ignorance and uncertainty quantification.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] However, the computational complexity of these algorithms is dependent on the number of propositions (classes), and can lead to a much higher computation time when compared to other machine learning approaches.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Rule-based machine learning (RBML) is a branch of machine learning that automatically discovers and learns 'rules' from data.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] It provides interpretable models, making it useful for decision-making in fields like healthcare, fraud detection, and cybersecurity.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Key RBML techniques includes learning classifier systems, association rule learning, artificial immune systems, and other similar models.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] These methods extract patterns from data and evolve rules over time.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Typically, machine learning models require a high quantity of reliable data to perform accurate predictions.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] When training a machine learning model, machine learning engineers need to target and collect a large and representative sample of data.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Data from the training set can be as varied as a corpus of text, a collection of images, sensor data, and data collected from individual users of a service.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Overfitting is something to watch out for when training a machine learning model.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Trained models derived from biased or non-evaluated data can result in skewed or undesired predictions.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Biased models may result in detrimental outcomes, thereby furthering the negative impacts on society or objectives.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Algorithmic bias is a potential result of data not being fully prepared for training.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning ethics is becoming a field of study and, notably, becoming integrated within machine learning engineering teams.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Federated learning is an adapted form of distributed artificial intelligence to train machine learning models that decentralises the training process, allowing for users' privacy to be maintained by not needing to send their data to a centralised server.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] This also increases efficiency by decentralising the training process to many devices.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] For example, Gboard uses federated machine learning to train search query prediction models on users' mobile phones without having to send individual searches back to Google.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] In 2006, the media-services provider Netflix held the first "Netflix Prize" competition to find a program to better predict user preferences and improve the accuracy of its existing Cinematch movie recommendation algorithm by at least 10%.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] A joint team made up of researchers from AT&T Labs-Research in collaboration with the teams Big Chaos and Pragmatic Theory built an ensemble model to win the Grand Prize in 2009 for $1 million.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Shortly after the prize was awarded, Netflix realised that viewers' ratings were not the best indicators of their viewing patterns ("everything is a recommendation") and they changed their recommendation engine accordingly.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] In 2010, an article in *The Wall Street Journal* noted the use of machine learning by Rebellion Research to predict the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] In 2012, co-founder of Sun Microsystems, Vinod Khosla, predicted that 80% of medical doctors jobs would be lost in the next two decades to automated machine learning medical diagnostic software.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] In 2014, it was reported that a machine learning algorithm had been applied in the field of art history to study fine art paintings and that it may have revealed previously unrecognised influences among artists.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] In 2019 Springer Nature published the first research book created using machine learning.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] In 2020, machine learning technology was used to help make diagnoses and aid researchers in developing a cure for COVID-19.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning was recently applied to predict the pro-environmental behaviour of travellers.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Recently, machine learning technology was also applied to optimise smartphone's performance and thermal behaviour based on the user's interaction with the phone.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] When applied correctly, machine learning algorithms (MLAs) can utilise a wide range of company characteristics to predict stock returns without overfitting.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] By employing effective feature engineering and combining forecasts, MLAs can generate results that far surpass those obtained from basic linear techniques like OLS.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Recent advancements in machine learning have extended into the field of quantum chemistry, where novel algorithms now enable the prediction of solvent effects on chemical reactions, thereby offering new tools for chemists to tailor experimental conditions for optimal outcomes.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Machine Learning is becoming a useful tool to investigate and predict evacuation decision-making in large-scale and small-scale disasters.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Different solutions have been tested to predict if and when householders decide to evacuate during wildfires and hurricanes.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p01] Other applications have been focusing on pre evacuation decisions in building fires.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Although machine learning has been transformative in some fields, machine-learning programs often fail to deliver expected results.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Reasons for this are numerous: lack of (suitable) data, lack of access to the data, data bias, privacy problems, badly chosen tasks and algorithms, wrong tools and people, lack of resources, and evaluation problems.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] The "black box theory" poses another yet significant challenge.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Black box refers to a situation where the algorithm producing an output is entirely opaque, meaning that even the designers of an application cannot audit the pattern that the machine extracted from the data.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] The House of Lords Select Committee, which claimed that such an "intelligence system" that could have a "substantial impact on an individual's life" would not be considered acceptable unless it provided "a full and satisfactory explanation for the decisions" it makes.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] In 2018, a self-driving car from Uber failed to detect a pedestrian, who was killed after a collision.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Attempts to use machine learning in healthcare with the IBM Watson system failed to deliver even after years of time and billions of dollars invested.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Microsoft's Bing Chat chatbot has been reported to produce hostile and offensive response against its users.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Machine learning has been used as a strategy to update the evidence related to a systematic review and increased reviewer burden related to the growth of biomedical literature.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] While it has improved with training sets, it has not yet developed sufficiently to reduce the workload burden without limiting the necessary sensitivity for the findings research itself.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Explainable AI (XAI), or Interpretable AI, or Explainable Machine Learning (XML), is artificial intelligence (AI) in which humans can understand the decisions or predictions made by the AI.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] It contrasts with the "black box" concept in machine learning where even its designers cannot explain why an AI arrived at a specific decision.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] By refining the mental models of users of AI-powered systems and dismantling their misconceptions, XAI promises to help users perform more effectively.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] XAI may be an implementation of the social right to explanation.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Settling on a bad, overly complex theory gerrymandered to fit all the past training data is known as overfitting.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Many systems attempt to reduce overfitting by rewarding a theory in accordance with how well it fits the data but penalising the theory in accordance with how complex the theory is.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] It is unclear to what extent the phenomenon threatens the long-term development of such models, and some techniques have been proposed to mitigate the effect.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] , inconsistent carriage lengths, unnatural amounts of visual noise, and a carriage bending along its length as it rounds the turn.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] In the field of artificial intelligence (AI), a hallucination or artificial hallucination (also called bullshitting, confabulation, or delusion) is a response generated by AI that contains false or misleading information presented as fact.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] The term draws a loose analogy with human psychology, where a hallucination typically involves false *percepts*.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] For example, a chatbot powered by large language models (LLMs), like ChatGPT, may embed plausible-sounding random falsehoods within its generated content.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Detecting and mitigating errors and hallucinations pose significant challenges for practical deployment and reliability of LLMs in high-stakes scenarios, such as chip design, supply chain logistics, and medical diagnostics.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Some software engineers and statisticians have criticized the specific term "AI hallucination" for unreasonably anthropomorphizing computers.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Symbolic artificial intelligence models generally do not produce hallucinations, unlike large language models.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Learners can also be disappointed by "learning the wrong lesson".
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] A toy example is that an image classifier trained only on pictures of brown horses and black cats might conclude that all brown patches are likely to be horses.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Modifying these patterns on a legitimate image can result in "adversarial" images that the system misclassifies.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Adversarial vulnerabilities can also result in nonlinear systems or from non-pattern perturbations.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] For some systems, it is possible to change the output by only changing a single adversarially chosen pixel.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Machine learning models are often vulnerable to manipulation or evasion via adversarial machine learning.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Researchers have demonstrated how backdoors can be placed undetectably into classifying (e.g., for categories "spam" and "not spam" of posts) machine learning models that are often developed or trained by third parties.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Parties can change the classification of any input, including in cases for which a type of data/software transparency is provided, possibly including white-box access.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Classification of machine learning models can be validated by accuracy estimation techniques like the holdout method, which splits the data into a training and test set (conventionally 2/3 training set and 1/3 test set designation) and evaluates the performance of the training model on the test set.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] In comparison, the K-fold-cross-validation method randomly partitions the data into K subsets and then K experiments are performed each considering 1 subset for evaluation and the remaining K-1 subsets for training the model.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] In addition to the holdout and cross-validation methods, bootstrap, which samples n instances with replacement from the dataset, can be used to assess model accuracy.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] In addition to overall accuracy, investigators frequently report sensitivity and specificity, meaning true positive rate (TPR) and true negative rate (TNR), respectively.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Similarly, investigators sometimes report the false positive rate (FPR) as well as the false negative rate (FNR).
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] However, these rates are ratios that fail to reveal their numerators and denominators.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Receiver operating characteristic (ROC), along with the accompanying Area Under the ROC Curve (AUC), offer additional tools for classification model assessment.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Higher AUC is associated with a better performing model.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] The ethics of artificial intelligence covers a broad range of topics within AI that are considered to have particular ethical stakes.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] This includes algorithmic biases, fairness, accountability, transparency, privacy, and regulation, particularly where systems influence or automate human decision-making.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Some application areas may also have particularly important ethical implications, like healthcare, education, criminal justice, or the military.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Different machine learning approaches can suffer from different data biases.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] A machine learning system trained specifically on current customers may not be able to predict the needs of new customer groups that are not represented in the training data.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] When trained on human-made data, machine learning is likely to pick up the constitutional and unconscious biases already present in society.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Systems that are trained on datasets collected with biases may exhibit these biases upon use (algorithmic bias), thus digitising cultural prejudices.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] For example, in 1988, the UK's Commission for Racial Equality found that St.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] George's Medical School had been using a computer program trained from data of previous admissions staff and this program had denied nearly 60 candidates who were found to either be women or have non-European-sounding names.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Using job hiring data from a firm with racist hiring policies may lead to a machine learning system duplicating the bias by scoring job applicants by similarity to previous successful applicants.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Another example includes predictive policing company Geolitica's predictive algorithm that resulted in "disproportionately high levels of over-policing in low-income and minority communities" after being trained with historical crime data.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] In fact, according to research carried out by the Computing Research Association in 2021, "female faculty make up just 16.1%" of all faculty members who focus on AI among several universities around the world.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Furthermore, among the group of "new U.S. resident AI PhD graduates," 45% identified as white, 22.4% as Asian, 3.2% as Hispanic, and 2.4% as African American, which further demonstrates a lack of diversity in the field of AI.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Language models learned from data have been shown to contain human-like biases.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Because human languages contain biases, machines trained on language *corpora* will necessarily also learn these biases.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] In 2016, Microsoft tested Tay, a chatbot that learned from Twitter, and it quickly picked up racist and sexist language.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] In an experiment carried out by ProPublica, an investigative journalism organisation, a machine learning algorithm's insight into the recidivism rates among prisoners falsely flagged "black defendants high risk twice as often as white defendants".
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] In 2015, Google Photos once tagged a couple of black people as gorillas, which caused controversy.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] The gorilla label was subsequently removed, and in 2023, it still cannot recognise gorillas.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Similar issues with recognising non-white people have been found in many other systems.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Because of such challenges, the effective use of machine learning may take longer to be adopted in other domains.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Concern for fairness in machine learning, that is, reducing bias in machine learning and propelling its use for human good, is increasingly expressed by artificial intelligence scientists, including Fei-Fei Li, who said that "[t]here's nothing artificial about AI.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] It's inspired by people, it's created by people, and—most importantly—it impacts people.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] There are concerns among health care professionals that these systems might not be designed in the public's interest but as income-generating machines.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] This is especially true in the United States, where there is a long-standing ethical dilemma of improving health care, but also increasing profits.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] For example, the algorithms could be designed to provide patients with unnecessary tests or medication in which the algorithm's proprietary owners hold stakes.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] There is potential for machine learning in health care to provide professionals with an additional tool to diagnose, medicate, and plan recovery paths for patients, but this requires these biases to be mitigated.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Since the 2010s, advances in both machine learning algorithms and computer hardware have led to more efficient methods for training deep neural networks (a particular narrow subdomain of machine learning) that contain many layers of nonlinear hidden units.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] By 2019, graphics processing units (GPUs), often with AI-specific enhancements, had displaced CPUs as the dominant method of training large-scale commercial cloud AI.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] OpenAI estimated the hardware compute used in the largest deep learning projects from AlexNet (2012) to AlphaZero (2017), and found a 300,000-fold increase in the amount of compute required, with a doubling-time trendline of 3.4 months.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Tensor Processing Units (TPUs) are specialised hardware accelerators developed by Google specifically for machine learning workloads.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Unlike general-purpose GPUs and FPGAs, TPUs are optimised for tensor computations, making them particularly efficient for deep learning tasks such as training and inference.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] They are widely used in Google Cloud AI services and large-scale machine learning models like Google's DeepMind AlphaFold and large language models.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] TPUs leverage matrix multiplication units and high-bandwidth memory to accelerate computations while maintaining energy efficiency.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Since their introduction in 2016, TPUs have become a key component of AI infrastructure, especially in cloud-based environments.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Neuromorphic computing refers to a class of computing systems designed to emulate the structure and functionality of biological neural networks.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] These systems may be implemented through software-based simulations on conventional hardware or through specialised hardware architectures.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] A physical neural network is a specific type of neuromorphic hardware that relies on electrically adjustable materials, such as memristors, to emulate the function of neural synapses.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] The term "physical neural network" highlights the use of physical hardware for computation, as opposed to software-based implementations.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] It broadly refers to artificial neural networks that use materials with adjustable resistance to replicate neural synapses.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Embedded machine learning is a sub-field of machine learning where models are deployed on embedded systems with limited computing resources, such as wearable computers, edge devices and microcontrollers.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Running models directly on these devices eliminates the need to transfer and store data on cloud servers for further processing, thereby reducing the risk of data breaches, privacy leaks and theft of intellectual property, personal data and business secrets.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Embedded machine learning can be achieved through various techniques, such as hardware acceleration, approximate computing, and model optimization.
[src:kedro-pipelines/machine-learning-p02] Common optimization techniques include pruning, quantisation, knowledge distillation, low-rank factorisation, network architecture search, and parameter sharing.
[src:kedro-pipelines/main-readme-md] Kedro is a toolbox for production-ready data engineering and data science pipelines.
[src:kedro-pipelines/main-readme-md] It uses software engineering best practices to help you create data engineering and data science pipelines that are reproducible, maintainable, and modular.
[src:kedro-pipelines/main-readme-md] Kedro is an open-source Python framework hosted by the LF AI & Data Foundation.
[src:kedro-pipelines/main-readme-md] Our Get Started guide contains full installation instructions, and includes how to set up Python virtual environments.
[src:kedro-pipelines/main-readme-md] To access the latest Kedro version before its official release, install it from the `main` branch.
[src:kedro-pipelines/main-readme-md] The Kedro documentation first explains how to install Kedro and then introduces key Kedro concepts.
[src:kedro-pipelines/main-readme-md] You can then review the spaceflights tutorial to build a Kedro project for hands-on experience.
[src:kedro-pipelines/main-readme-md] For new and intermediate Kedro users, there's a comprehensive section on how to visualise Kedro projects using Kedro-Viz.
[src:kedro-pipelines/main-readme-md] Additional documentation explains how to work with Kedro and Jupyter notebooks, and there are a set of advanced user guides for advanced for key Kedro features.
[src:kedro-pipelines/main-readme-md] We also recommend the API reference documentation for further information.
[src:kedro-pipelines/main-readme-md] Kedro is built upon our collective best-practice (and mistakes) trying to deliver real-world ML applications that have vast amounts of raw unvetted data.
[src:kedro-pipelines/main-readme-md] Find out more about how Kedro can answer your use cases from the product FAQs on the Kedro website.
[src:kedro-pipelines/main-readme-md] The Kedro product team and a number of open source contributors from across the world maintain Kedro.
[src:kedro-pipelines/main-readme-md] Check out our guide to contributing to Kedro.
[src:kedro-pipelines/main-readme-md] There is a growing community around Kedro.
[src:kedro-pipelines/main-readme-md] We encourage you to ask and answer technical questions on Slack and bookmark the Linen archive of past discussions.
[src:kedro-pipelines/main-readme-md] We keep a list of technical FAQs in the Kedro documentation and you can find a growing list of blog posts, videos and projects that use Kedro over on the `awesome-kedro` GitHub repository.
[src:kedro-pipelines/main-readme-md] If you have created anything with Kedro we'd love to include it on the list.
[src:kedro-pipelines/main-readme-md] If you're an academic, Kedro can also help you, for example, as a tool to solve the problem of reproducible research.
[src:kedro-pipelines/main-readme-md] Use the "Cite this repository" button on our repository to generate a citation from the CITATION.cff file.
[src:kedro-pipelines/main-readme-md] We appreciate our community and want to stay connected.
[src:kedro-pipelines/main-readme-md] For that, we offer a public Coffee Chat format where we share updates and cool stuff around Kedro once every two weeks and give you time to ask your questions live.
[src:kedro-pipelines/main-readme-md] Check out the upcoming demo topics and dates at the Kedro Coffee Chat wiki page.
[src:kedro-pipelines/main-readme-md] Follow our Slack announcement channel to see Kedro Coffee Chat announcements and access demo recordings.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] In software engineering, a **pipeline** consists of a chain of processing elements (processes, threads, coroutines, functions, *etc.*), arranged so that the output of each element is the input of the next.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] The concept is analogous to a physical pipeline.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] Usually some amount of buffering is provided between consecutive elements.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] The information that flows in these pipelines is often a stream of records, bytes, or bits, and the elements of a pipeline may be called filters.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] This is also called the **pipe(s) and filters** design pattern which is monolithic.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] Its advantages are simplicity and low cost while its disadvantages are lack of elasticity, fault tolerance and scalability.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] Connecting elements into a pipeline is analogous to function composition.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] Narrowly speaking, a pipeline is linear and one-directional, though sometimes the term is applied to more general flows.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] For example, a primarily one-directional pipeline may have some communication in the other direction, known as a *return channel* or *backchannel,* as in the lexer hack, or a pipeline may be fully bi-directional.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] Flows with one-directional trees and directed acyclic graph topologies behave similarly to linear pipelines.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] The lack of cycles in such flows makes them simple, and thus they may be loosely referred to as "pipelines".
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] Pipelines are often implemented in a multitasking OS, by launching all elements at the same time as processes, and automatically servicing the data read requests by each process with the data written by the upstream process.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] This can be called a *multiprocessed pipeline.* In this way, the scheduler will naturally switch the CPU among the processes so as to minimize its idle time.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] In other common models, elements are implemented as lightweight threads or as coroutines to reduce the OS overhead often involved with processes.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] Depending on the OS, threads may be scheduled directly by the OS or by a thread manager.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] Coroutines are always scheduled by a coroutine manager of some form.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] Read and write requests are usually blocking operations.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] This means that the execution of the source process, upon writing, is suspended until all data can be written to the destination process.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] Likewise, the execution of the destination process, upon reading, is suspended until at least some of the requested data can be obtained from the source process.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] This cannot lead to a deadlock, where both processes would wait indefinitely for each other to respond, since at least one of the processes will soon have its request serviced by the operating system, and continue to run.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] For performance, most operating systems implementing pipes use pipe buffers, which allow the source process to provide more data than the destination process is currently able or willing to receive.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] Under most Unixes and Unix-like operating systems, a special command is also available, typically called "buffer", that implements a pipe buffer of potentially much larger and configurable size.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] This command can be useful if the destination process is significantly slower than the source process, but it is desired that the source process complete its task as soon as possible.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] E.g., if the source process consists of a command which reads an audio track from a CD and the destination process consists of a command which compresses the waveform audio data to a format like MP3.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] In this case, buffering the entire track in a pipe buffer would allow the CD drive to spin down more quickly, and enable the user to remove the CD from the drive before the encoding process has finished.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] Such a buffer command can be implemented using system calls for reading and writing data.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] Wasteful busy waiting can be avoided by using facilities such as poll or select or multithreading.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] CMS Pipelines is a port of the pipeline idea to VM/CMS and z/OS systems.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] It supports much more complex pipeline structures than Unix shells, with steps taking multiple input streams and producing multiple output streams.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] (Such functionality is supported by the Unix kernel, but few programs use it as it makes for complicated syntax and blocking modes, although some shells do support it via arbitrary file descriptor assignment).
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] Traditional application programs on IBM mainframe operating systems have no standard input and output streams to allow redirection or piping.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] Instead of spawning processes with external programs, CMS Pipelines features a lightweight dispatcher to concurrently execute instances of more than 200 built-in programs that implement typical UNIX utilities and interface to devices and operating system services.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] In addition to the built-in programs, CMS Pipelines defines a framework to allow user-written REXX programs with input and output streams that can be used in the pipeline.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] Data on IBM mainframes typically resides in a record-oriented filesystem and connected I/O devices operate in record mode rather than stream mode.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] As a consequence, data in CMS Pipelines is handled in record mode.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] For text files, a record holds one line of text.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] In general, CMS Pipelines does not buffer the data but passes records of data in a lock-step fashion from one program to the next.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] This ensures a deterministic flow of data through a network of interconnected pipelines.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] Beside byte stream-based pipelines, there are also object pipelines.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] In an object pipeline, processing elements output objects instead of text.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] PowerShell includes an internal object pipeline that transfers .NET objects between functions within the PowerShell runtime.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] Channels, found in the Limbo programming language, are other examples of this metaphor.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] Graphical environments such as RISC OS and ROX Desktop also use pipelines.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] Rather than providing a save dialog box containing a file manager to let the user specify where a program should write data, RISC OS and ROX provide a save dialog box containing an icon (and a field to specify the name).
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] The destination is specified by dragging and dropping the icon.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] The user can drop the icon anywhere an already-saved file could be dropped, including onto icons of other programs.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] If the icon is dropped onto a program's icon, it is loaded and the contents that would otherwise have been saved are passed in on the new program's standard input stream.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] For instance, a user browsing the world-wide web might come across a .gz compressed image which they want to edit and re-upload.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] Using GUI pipelines, they could drag the link to their de-archiving program, drag the icon representing the extracted contents to their image editor, edit it, open the save as dialog, and drag its icon to their uploading software.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] Conceptually, this method could be used with a conventional save dialog box, but this would require the user's programs to have an obvious and easily accessible location in the filesystem.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] As this is often not the case, GUI pipelines are rare.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] The name "pipeline" comes from a rough analogy with physical plumbing in that a pipeline usually allows information to flow in only one direction, like water often flows in a pipe.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] Pipes and filters can be viewed as a form of functional programming, using byte streams as data objects.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] More specifically, they can be seen as a particular form of monad for I/O.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] The concept of pipeline is also central to the Cocoon web development framework or to any XProc (the W3C Standards) implementations, where it allows a source stream to be modified before eventual display.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] This pattern encourages the use of text streams as the input and output of programs.
[src:kedro-pipelines/pipeline-software] This reliance on text has to be accounted when creating graphic shells to text programs.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] The first to stress the importance of reproducibility in science was the Anglo-Irish chemist Robert Boyle, in England in the 17th century.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] Boyle's air pump was designed to generate and study vacuum, which at the time was a very controversial concept.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] Indeed, distinguished philosophers such as René Descartes and Thomas Hobbes denied the very possibility of vacuum existence.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] Historians of science Steven Shapin and Simon Schaffer, in their 1985 book *Leviathan and the Air-Pump*, describe the debate between Boyle and Hobbes, ostensibly over the nature of vacuum, as fundamentally an argument about how useful knowledge should be gained.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] Boyle, a pioneer of the experimental method, maintained that the foundations of knowledge should be constituted by experimentally produced facts, which can be made believable to a scientific community by their reproducibility.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] By repeating the same experiment over and over again, Boyle argued, the certainty of fact will emerge.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] The air pump, which in the 17th century was a complicated and expensive apparatus to build, also led to one of the first documented disputes over the reproducibility of a particular scientific phenomenon.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] In the 1660s, the Dutch scientist Christiaan Huygens built his own air pump in Amsterdam, the first one outside the direct management of Boyle and his assistant at the time Robert Hooke.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] Huygens reported an effect he termed "anomalous suspension", in which water appeared to levitate in a glass jar inside his air pump (in fact suspended over an air bubble), but Boyle and Hooke could not replicate this phenomenon in their own pumps.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] As Shapin and Schaffer describe, "it became clear that unless the phenomenon could be produced in England with one of the two pumps available, then no one in England would accept the claims Huygens had made, or his competence in working the pump".
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] Huygens was finally invited to England in 1663, and under his personal guidance Hooke was able to replicate anomalous suspension of water.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] Following this Huygens was elected a Foreign Member of the Royal Society.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] However, Shapin and Schaffer also note that "the accomplishment of replication was dependent on contingent acts of judgment.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] One cannot write down a formula saying when replication was or was not achieved".
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] The philosopher of science Karl Popper noted briefly in his famous 1934 book *The Logic of Scientific Discovery* that "non-reproducible single occurrences are of no significance to science".
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] Such assertions express a common dogma in modern science that reproducibility is a necessary condition (although not necessarily sufficient) for establishing a scientific fact, and in practice for establishing scientific authority in any field of knowledge.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] However, as noted above by Shapin and Schaffer, this dogma is not well-formulated quantitatively, such as statistical significance for instance, and therefore it is not explicitly established how many times must a fact be replicated to be considered reproducible.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] Two major steps are naturally distinguished in connection with reproducibility of experimental or observational studies: when new data are obtained in the attempt to achieve it, the term *replicability* is often used, and the new study is a *replication* or *replicate* of the original one.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] Obtaining the same results when analyzing the data set of the original study again with the same procedures, many authors use the term *reproducibility* in a narrow, technical sense coming from its use in computational research.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] *Repeatability* is related to the *repetition* of the experiment within the same study by the same researchers.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] Reproducibility in the original, wide sense is only acknowledged if a replication performed by an *independent researcher team* is successful.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] The terms reproducibility and replicability sometimes appear even in the scientific literature with reversed meaning, as different research fields settled on their own definitions for the same terms.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] In chemistry, the terms reproducibility and repeatability are used with a specific quantitative meaning.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] In inter-laboratory experiments, a concentration or other quantity of a chemical substance is measured repeatedly in different laboratories to assess the variability of the measurements.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] Then, the standard deviation of the difference between two values obtained within the same laboratory is called repeatability.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] The standard deviation for the difference between two measurement from different laboratories is called *reproducibility*.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] These measures are related to the more general concept of variance components in metrology.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] The term *reproducible research* refers to the idea that scientific results should be documented in such a way that their deduction is fully transparent.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] This requires a detailed description of the methods used to obtain the data and making the full dataset and the code to calculate the results easily accessible.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] This is the essential part of open science.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] To make any research project computationally reproducible, general practice involves all data and files being clearly separated, labelled, and documented.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] All operations should be fully documented and automated as much as practicable, avoiding manual intervention where feasible.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] The workflow should be designed as a sequence of smaller steps that are combined so that the intermediate outputs from one step directly feed as inputs into the next step.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] Version control should be used as it lets the history of the project be easily reviewed and allows for the documenting and tracking of changes in a transparent manner.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] A basic workflow for reproducible research involves data acquisition, data processing and data analysis.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] Data acquisition primarily consists of obtaining primary data from a primary source such as surveys, field observations, experimental research, or obtaining data from an existing source.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] Data processing involves the processing and review of the raw data collected in the first stage, and includes data entry, data manipulation and filtering and may be done using software.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] The data should be digitized and prepared for data analysis.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] Data may be analysed with the use of software to interpret or visualise statistics or data to produce the desired results of the research such as quantitative results including figures and tables.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] The use of software and automation enhances the reproducibility of research methods.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] There are systems that facilitate such documentation, like the R Markdown language or the Jupyter notebook.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] The Open Science Framework provides a platform and useful tools to support reproducible research.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] Psychology has seen a renewal of internal concerns about irreproducible results (see the entry on replicability crisis for empirical results on success rates of replications).
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] Researchers showed in a 2006 study that, of 141 authors of a publication from the American Psychological Association (APA) empirical articles, 103 (73%) did not respond with their data over a six-month period.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] In a follow-up study published in 2015, it was found that 246 out of 394 contacted authors of papers in APA journals did not share their data upon request (62%).
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] In a 2012 paper, it was suggested that researchers should publish data along with their works, and a dataset was released alongside as a demonstration.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] In 2017, an article published in *Scientific Data* suggested that this may not be sufficient and that the whole analysis context should be disclosed.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] In economics, concerns have been raised in relation to the credibility and reliability of published research.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] In other sciences, reproducibility is regarded as fundamental and is often a prerequisite to research being published, however in economic sciences it is not seen as a priority of the greatest importance.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] Most peer-reviewed economic journals do not take any substantive measures to ensure that published results are reproducible, however, the top economics journals have been moving to adopt mandatory data and code archives.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] There is low or no incentives for researchers to share their data, and authors would have to bear the costs of compiling data into reusable forms.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] Economic research is often not reproducible as only a portion of journals have adequate disclosure policies for datasets and program code, and even if they do, authors frequently do not comply with them or they are not enforced by the publisher.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] A Study of 599 articles published in 37 peer-reviewed journals revealed that while some journals have achieved significant compliance rates, significant portion have only partially complied, or not complied at all.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] On an article level, the average compliance rate was 47.5%; and on a journal level, the average compliance rate was 38%, ranging from 13% to 99%.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] A 2018 study published in the journal *PLOS ONE* found that 14.4% of a sample of public health statistics researchers had shared their data or code or both.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] There have been initiatives to improve reporting and hence reproducibility in the medical literature for many years, beginning with the CONSORT initiative, which is now part of a wider initiative, the EQUATOR Network.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] This group has recently turned its attention to how better reporting might reduce waste in research, especially biomedical research.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] Reproducible research is key to new discoveries in pharmacology.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] A Phase I discovery will be followed by Phase II reproductions as a drug develops towards commercial production.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] In recent decades Phase II success has fallen from 28% to 18%.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] A 2011 study found that 65% of medical studies were inconsistent when re-tested, and only 6% were completely reproducible.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] Some efforts have been made to increase replicability beyond the social and biomedical sciences.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] Studies in the humanities tend to rely more on expertise and hermeneutics which may make replicability more difficult.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] Nonetheless, some efforts have been made to call for more transparency and documentation in the humanities.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] Hideyo Noguchi became famous for correctly identifying the bacterial agent of syphilis, but also claimed that he could culture this agent in his laboratory.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] Nobody else has been able to produce this latter result.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] In March 1989, University of Utah chemists Stanley Pons and Martin Fleischmann reported the production of excess heat that could only be explained by a nuclear process ("cold fusion").
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] The report was astounding given the simplicity of the equipment: it was essentially an electrolysis cell containing heavy water and a palladium cathode which rapidly absorbed the deuterium produced during electrolysis.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] The news media reported on the experiments widely, and it was a front-page item on many newspapers around the world (see science by press conference).
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] Over the next several months others tried to replicate the experiment, but were unsuccessful.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] Nikola Tesla claimed as early as 1899 to have used a high frequency current to light gas-filled lamps from over 25 miles (40 km) away without using wires.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] In 1904 he built Wardenclyffe Tower on Long Island to demonstrate means to send and receive power without connecting wires.
[src:kedro-pipelines/reproducibility] The facility was never fully operational and was not completed due to economic problems, so no attempt to reproduce his first result was ever carried out.
